  • Resisting or Obstructing an Officer [Modifiers: Repeater], a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 946.41(1).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

[MK] case called at 1:46am.
Defendant David Rodulfo in court with Attorney Steven J Luchsinger.   ADA Monica Hall appears for the State of Wisconsin.  

Maximum penalties recited; Constitutional rights reviewed; plea of " No Contest " entered; factual basis stipulated; victim rights compliance verified; the Court accepts plea, finds Defendant guilty, and orders Judgment of Conviction entered.
Repeater finding made. 

The Court sentences Mr. Rodulfo to 2 years, with an Initial Term of Confinement in Prison of 18 months, and the maximum time to serve on Extended Supervision of 6 months.  
The Court finds that the Defendant is not eligible for the Challenge Incarceration Program "Boot Camp".
The Court finds that the Defendant is not eligible for the Substance Abuse Program.
The Court gives 1 day credit for time already served.

The Court STAYS this Sentence and places Mr. Rodulfo on Probation for one year, with conditions: 
--no possession or consumption of alcohol
--no possession or consumption of illegal drugs
--no presence in bars, taverns, liquor stores
--not to commit any acts of violence or make any threats to any person
--to undergo any type of assesssment, treatment, therapy or counseling as required by the Agent
--to pay costs and fees, including the $200 DNA surcharge, $33 in subpoena fees, and $33 in summons fees
--to reimburse Jefferson County for court-appointed attorney fees
